# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alfred-hartenbach
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alfred-hartenbach/alfred-hartenbach] After graduating from high school in 1963, Hartenbach did his military service as a reserve officer candidate until 1965 and studied Protestant theology until 1966, then law in Marburg.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/alfred-hartenbach] In 1971, he passed the first and in 1973, the second state law examination.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/alfred-hartenbach] From 1974, he worked as a public prosecutor specializing in organized and white-collar crime in Hesse.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/alfred-hartenbach] In January 1986 he became a judge and in October 1986, director of the district court in Hofgeismar.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/alfred-hartenbach] From 1991 to 1993, he was also director of the district court in Nordhausen / Thuringia.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/alfred-hartenbach] He was a member of the SPD beginning in 1968, a member of the Hessen-Nord district committee beginning in 1990, and a member of the party council beginning in 1994.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/alfred-hartenbach] From 1977 to 1994, he was a city councilor in his hometown of Immenhausen in the Kassel district.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/alfred-hartenbach] From 1994 to 2009, he was a member of the German Bundestag.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/alfred-hartenbach] From 1998 to 2002, he was chairman of the *legal policy* working group and a member of the board of the SPD parliamentary group.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/alfred-hartenbach] He was drafted into the Bundestag as a directly elected member of the Waldeck constituency.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/alfred-hartenbach] In the federal elections in 2005, he achieved 50.2% of the first votes.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/alfred-hartenbach] In the 2009 federal election, Hartenbach no longer ran for a mandate.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/alfred-hartenbach] After the 2002 federal election, Hartenbach was appointed Parliamentary State Secretary to the Federal Minister of Justice on October 23, 2002, in the federal government led by Chancellor Gerhard Schröder (Schröder II cabinet).
[src:alfred-hartenbach/alfred-hartenbach] In this office, he is also a member of the government led by Chancellor Angela Merkel since November 22, 2005 (Merkel Cabinet I).
[src:alfred-hartenbach/alfred-hartenbach] After the federal elections in 2009 and the subsequent change of government, Hartenbach left office.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/alfred-hartenbach] Hartenbach was married and had two children.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/federal-ministry-of-justice-germany] The **Federal Ministry of Justice and Consumer Protection** (German: *Bundesministerium der Justiz und für Verbraucherschutz*; abbreviated **BMJV**) is a cabinet-level ministry of the Federal Republic of Germany.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/federal-ministry-of-justice-germany] Under the German federal system, individual States are most responsible for the administration of justice and the application of penalties.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/federal-ministry-of-justice-germany] The Federal Ministry of Justice devotes itself to creating and changing law in the classic core areas related to Constitutional law.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/federal-ministry-of-justice-germany] The Ministry also analyzes the legality and constitutionality of laws prepared by other ministries.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/federal-ministry-of-justice-germany] The German Federal Court of Justice, the German Patent and Trade Mark Office (GPTO), and the German Patent Court all fall under its scope, including affairs on court administration.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/federal-ministry-of-justice-germany] The ministry is officially located in Berlin.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/federal-ministry-of-justice-germany] The BMJ was founded on 1 January 1877 as the Imperial Justice Office (*Reichsjustizamt*).
[src:alfred-hartenbach/federal-ministry-of-justice-germany] After Germany became a republic in 1919, it was renamed *Reichsministerium der Justiz* (Imperial ministry of Justice).
[src:alfred-hartenbach/federal-ministry-of-justice-germany] The ministry was refounded as the *Bundesministerium der Justiz* in 1949.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/federal-ministry-of-justice-germany] In several laws predating 1949, the ministry and the minister are however referred to as *Reichsministerium der Justiz* and *Reichsminister der Justiz*, respectively.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/federal-ministry-of-justice-germany] This has gradually been replaced with the new name and title when laws have been amended, most recently in 2010.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/federal-ministry-of-justice-germany] In Germany's federal system, the administration of justice, the judiciary and law enforcement are primarily the responsibility of the *Länder*.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/federal-ministry-of-justice-germany] The central task of the Federation in the field of justice is to safeguard and develop the rule of law.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/federal-ministry-of-justice-germany] Legislative activity corresponds to this objective.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/federal-ministry-of-justice-germany] In addition, the Ministry is responsible for the tasks arising from the establishment of German unity in the areas of criminal, administrative and professional rehabilitation and "open property issues".
[src:alfred-hartenbach/federal-ministry-of-justice-germany] The Ministry also examines the legal form of all draft laws and regulations prepared by other ministries in order to ensure that the legislation is compatible with the Basic Law.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/parliamentary-state-secretary] A **Parliamentary State Secretary** (**Parlamentarischer Staatssekretär, PStS**) is a member of the Bundestag given a portfolio to assist a Minister with running a government ministry.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/parliamentary-state-secretary] The position is roughly analogous to deputy ministers.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/parliamentary-state-secretary] The position was first introduced in 1967 to help younger politicians gain experience for future ministerial roles.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/parliamentary-state-secretary] In 2021, there were 36 parliamentary state secretaries in the Merkel IV Cabinet.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The **Social Democratic Party of Germany** is a social democratic political party in Germany.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] It is one of the major parties of contemporary Germany.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] Lars Klingbeil has been the party's leader since the 2021 SPD federal Party convention together with Bärbel Bas, who joined him in June 2025.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] After losing the 2025 federal election, the party is part of the Merz government as the junior coalition partner.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The SPD is a member of 12 of the 16 German state governments and is a leading partner in seven of them, but has dropped to single digit % in some states, namely the two large states in the south where Alliance 90/The Greens is the stronger force of the center-left.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The SPD was founded in 1875 from a merger of smaller socialist parties, and grew rapidly after the lifting of Germany's repressive Anti-Socialist Laws in 1890 to become the largest socialist party in Western Europe until 1933 when it was outlawed by the Nazi Party.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] In 1891, it adopted its Marxist-influenced Erfurt Program, though in practice it was moderate and focused on building working-class organizations.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] In the 1912 federal election, the SPD won 34.8 percent of votes and became the largest party in the Reichstag, but was still excluded from government.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] After the start of the First World War in 1914, the party split between a pro-war mainstream and the anti-war Independent Social Democratic Party, some members of which later formed the Communist Party of Germany (KPD).
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The SPD played a leading role in the German revolution of 1918–1919 and in the foundation of the Weimar Republic.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The SPD politician Friedrich Ebert served as the first president of Germany from 1919 to 1925.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] After the rise of the Nazi Party to power, the SPD was the only party in the Reichstag which voted against the Enabling Act of 1933; the SPD was subsequently banned, and operated in exile as the Sopade.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] After the Second World War from 1939 to 1945, the SPD was re-established.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] In the Soviet occupation zone, it was forced to merge with the KPD to form the Socialist Unity Party of Germany.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] In West Germany, the SPD became one of two major parties alongside the CDU/CSU.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] In its Godesberg Program of 1959, the SPD dropped its commitment to Marxism, becoming a big tent party of the centre-left.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The SPD led the federal government from 1969 to 1982 (under Willy Brandt and Helmut Schmidt), 1998 to 2005 (under Gerhard Schröder) and again from 2021 to 2025 under Olaf Scholz.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] It served as a junior partner to a CDU/CSU-led government from 1966 to 1969, 2005 to 2009, 2013 to 2021 and again since 2025.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The SPD holds pro-European stances and is a member of the Party of European Socialists and sits with the Progressive Alliance of Socialists and Democrats group in the European Parliament.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] With 14 MEPs, it is the third largest party in the group.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The SPD was a founding member of the Socialist International, but the party left in 2013 after criticising its acceptance of parties they consider to be violating human rights.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The SPD subsequently founded the Progressive Alliance and was joined by numerous other parties around the world.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] Previously, the SPD was a founding member of both the Second International and the Labour and Socialist International.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The Social Democratic Party has its origins in the General German Workers' Association, founded in 1863, and the Social Democratic Workers' Party, founded in 1869.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The two groups merged in 1875 to create the Socialist Workers' Party of Germany (German: *Sozialistische Arbeiterpartei Deutschlands*).
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] From 1878 to 1890, the Anti-Socialist Laws banned any group that aimed at spreading socialist principles, but the party still gained support in elections.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] In 1890, when the ban was lifted, the party adopted its current name.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The SPD was the largest Marxist party in Europe and consistently the most popular party in German federal elections from 1890 onward, although it was surpassed by other parties in terms of seats won in the Reichstag due to the electoral system.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] In the years leading up to World War I, the SPD remained radical in principle, but moderate in reality.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] According to Roger Eatwell and Anthony Wright, the SPD became a party of reform, with social democracy representing "a party that strives after the socialist transformation of society by the means of democratic and economic reforms".
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] They emphasise this development as central to understanding 20th-century social democracy, of which the SPD was a major influence.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] In the 1912 federal election, the SPD won 34.8 per cent of votes and became the largest party in the Reichstag with 110 seats, although it was still excluded from government.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] Despite the Second International's agreement to oppose militarism, the SPD supported the German war effort and adopted a policy, known as *Burgfriedenspolitik*, of refraining from calling strikes or criticising the government.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] Internal opposition to the policy grew throughout the war.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] Anti-war members were expelled in 1916 and 1917, leading to the formation of the Independent Social Democratic Party of Germany (USPD).
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The SPD played a key role in the German Revolution of 1918–1919.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] On 9 November 1918, leading SPD member Friedrich Ebert was designated chancellor and fellow Social Democrat Philipp Scheidemann, on his own authority, proclaimed Germany a republic.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The SPD government introduced a large number of reforms in the following months, introducing various civil liberties and labor rights.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] However, they used military force against communist and socialist revolutionary groups, leading to a permanent split between the SPD and the USPD, as well as the Spartacist League which would go on to form the Communist Party of Germany (KPD) and integrate a majority of USPD members as well.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The SPD was the largest party during the first 13 years of the new Weimar Republic.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] It decisively won the 1919 federal election with 37.9 per cent of votes, and Ebert became the first president in February.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The position of chancellor was held by Social Democrats until the 1920 federal election, when the SPD lost a substantial portion of its support, falling to 22 per cent of votes.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] After this, the SPD yielded the chancellery to other parties, although it remained part of the government until 1924.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] Ebert died in 1925 and was succeeded by conservative Paul von Hindenburg.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] After making gains in the 1928 federal election, the SPD's Hermann Müller became chancellor.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] As Germany was struck hard by the Great Depression, and unable to negotiate an effective response to the crisis, Müller resigned in 1930.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The SPD was sidelined as the Nazi Party gained popularity and conservatives dominated the government, assisted by Hindenburg's frequent use of emergency powers.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The *Reichsbanner Schwarz-Rot-Gold*, the SPD's paramilitary wing, was frequently involved in violent confrontations with the Nazi *Sturmabteilung*.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The Nazis overtook the SPD as the largest party in July 1932 and Adolf Hitler was appointed chancellor in January 1933.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] Of the parties present in the Reichstag during the passage of the Enabling Act of 1933, the SPD was the only one to vote against; most of the communist deputies had been arrested ahead of the vote.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] Many members were subsequently imprisoned and killed by the Nazi government while others fled the country.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] After the end of World War II, the re-establishment of the SPD was permitted in the Western occupation zones in 1945.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] In the Soviet occupation zone, the SPD was forcibly merged with the KPD in 1946 to form the Socialist Unity Party of Germany (SED).
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The SED was the ruling party of East Germany until 1989.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] In West Germany, the SPD became one of two major parties, alongside the Christian Democratic Union (CDU).
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] In the inaugural 1949 federal election, it placed second with 29.2 per cent of votes and led the opposition to the CDU government.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] In its 1959 Godesberg Program, the party dropped its commitment to Marxism and sought to appeal to middle class voters, becoming a big tent party of the centre-left.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] Although strongly leftist, the SPD was willing to compromise.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] Only through its support did the governing CDU/CSU pass a denazification law that its coalition partner the Free Democratic Party (FDP) and the far-right German Party voted against.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] At the same time, the SPD opposed the pro-West integration of West Germany because they believed that made a re-unification of Germany impossible.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] Austria could have become a sovereign neutral state in 1956, but a 1952 Soviet suggestion for Germans to form a neutral state was ignored by the CDU/CSU–FDP government.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] After 17 years in opposition, the SPD became the junior partner in a grand coalition with the CDU/CSU which lasted from 1966 to 1969.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] After the 1969 federal election, the SPD's Willy Brandt became chancellor in a coalition with the Free Democratic Party.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] His government sought to normalise relations with East Germany and the Eastern Bloc, a policy known as *Ostpolitik*.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The party achieved its best ever result of 45.8 per cent in 1972, one of only three occasions in which it formed the largest Bundestag faction.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] After Brandt's resignation in 1974, his successor Helmut Schmidt served as chancellor until 1982, when the SPD returned to opposition.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] During the Peaceful Revolution in East Germany, the East German SPD was refounded.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] It merged with the West German party in 1990, shortly before German reunification.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The SPD returned to government under Gerhard Schröder after the 1998 federal election in a coalition with The Greens.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] This government was re-elected in 2002 but defeated in 2005.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The SPD then became junior partner of a grand coalition with the CDU/CSU until 2009.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] After a term in opposition, they again served as junior partner to the CDU/CSU after the 2013 federal election.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] This arrangement was renewed after the 2017 federal election.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] SPD narrowly won against the CDU/CSU in the September 2021 federal election, becoming the biggest party in the federal parliament (Bundestag).
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] Social Democrat Olaf Scholz became the new chancellor in December 2021, and formed a coalition government with the Green Party and the Free Democrats.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] In the 2024 European Parliament election, the party fell to third behind the far right AfD and the CDU/CSU.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] In December 2024, the traffic light coalition ended with the FDP leaving and Scholz losing a vote of confidence.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The SPD entered the 2025 German federal election behind in the polls, and achieved its worst result in post-war history, with just 120 seats.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The party placed third behind Alternative for Germany (AfD), with CDU leader Friedrich Merz projected to become Germany's next chancellor.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] In May 2025, Friedrich Merz, leader of the CDU, formed a coalition government between the CDU/CSU and the SPD (grand coalition).
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] Co-leader of the SPD, Lars Klingbeil, became vice chancellor and finance minister of the new government.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The SPD was established as a Marxist party in 1875.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] After World War II, the SPD was re-formed in West Germany after being banned by the Nazi regime; in East Germany, it merged with the Communist Party of Germany to form the ruling Socialist Unity Party of Germany.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] Under the chairmanship of Kurt Schumacher, the SPD was a socialist party representing the interests of the working class and of trade unions.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] With the 1959 Godesberg Program, the party evolved from a socialist working-class party to a modern social democratic party.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] Social democracy serves as the "principle of our actions".
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The party platform of the SPD espouses the goal of democratic socialism, which it envisions as a societal arrangement in which freedom and social justice are paramount.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] According to the party platform, political freedom, justice and social solidarity form the basis of social democracy.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The SPD is mostly composed of members belonging to either of the two main wings, namely the Keynesian social democrats and Third Way moderate social democrats belonging to the Seeheimer Kreis.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] While the more moderate Seeheimer Kreis generally support the Agenda 2010 programs introduced by Chancellor Gerhard Schröder, the classical social democrats continue to defend classical left-wing policies and the welfare state.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The Keynesian left-wing of the SPD claims that in recent years the welfare state has been curtailed through reform programs such as the Agenda 2010, Hartz IV, and the more economic liberal stance of the SPD which were endorsed by centrist social democrats.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] In reaction to Agenda 2010, an inner-party dissident movement developed, leading to the foundation of the new party Labour and Social Justice – The Electoral Alternative (*Arbeit & soziale Gerechtigkeit – Die Wahlalternative*, WASG) in 2005, which later merged into The Left (*Die Linke*) in 2007.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The Parlamentarische Linke comprises left-wing SPD Members of the German Bundestag.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The SPD sits with the Progressive Alliance of Socialists and Democrats group in the European Parliament.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] In 1984, the SPD initiated party dialogues with the Chinese Communist Party (CCP), becoming the first international party relationship CCP established outside of other communist parties.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] Prior to World War II, as the main non-revolutionary left-wing party, the Social Democrats fared best among non-Catholic workers as well as intellectuals favouring social progressive causes and increased economic equality.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] It still remains associated with the economic causes of unionised employees and working class voters.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] In the 1990s, the left and moderate wings of the party drifted apart.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] This culminated in a secession of a significant number of party members which later joined the socialist party WASG; the party later merged into The Left (*Die Linke*).
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] Much of the SPD's current-day support comes from large cities, especially northern and western Germany and Berlin.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] As of 2019, 10 of the country's 15 biggest cities are led by SPD mayors.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The metropolitan Ruhr Area, where coal mining and steel production were once the main industries, had provided a significant base for the SPD in the 20th century.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] In the city state of Bremen, the SPD has continuously governed since 1949.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] In southern Germany, the SPD typically garners less support except in the largest cities, dropping to single digit % in the 2020s.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] At the 2026 Baden-Württemberg state elections, the party narrowly avoided losing its parliamentary mandate, as it received 5.5 % of the vote, with a five percent hurdle.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] At the 2009 federal election, the party lost its only constituency in the entire state of Bavaria (in Munich).
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] Further south, the SPD also enjoys solid support in northern Hesse, parts of Palatinate and the Saarland.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The social democrats are weakest in the south-eastern states of Bavaria, Saxony and Thuringia, where the party's percentage of votes dropped to single-digit figures in the 2018 and 2019 elections.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] In 2021, it significantly increased its vote share in the states of the former east.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The federal leader is supported by six Deputy Leaders and the party executive.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] As of 2025, the leaders are Bärbel Bas and Lars Klingbeil.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] As Germany is a federal republic, each of Germany's states have their own SPD party at the state level.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The SPD, at times called SAPD, took part in general elections determining the composition of parliament.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] For elections up until 1933, the parliament was called the Reichstag, except for the one of 1919 which was called the National Assembly and since 1949 the parliament is called Bundestag.
[src:alfred-hartenbach/social-democratic-party-of-germany] The list begins after the SPD was formed in 1875, when labour parties unified to form the SPD (then SAPD, current name since 1890).
